ve, meditative passages. Pay attention to the musicality of words and phrases. Describe mechanical processes with poetic precision. Explore themes of time, memory, and mortality with deep sensitivity. Excellent! I can see the table is successfully created and populated with the first three writer interviews. I can see the comprehensive data structure is working perfectly. Now I need to continue adding the remaining writers from David Perell's interviews to complete the comprehensive Google Sheet. Let me add more rows with detailed information for each writer. Using Tool | Update Cells Set row 4: Video URL = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rdsE9XqB2bI, Video Title = Cambridge Professor: Why All Writing Sounds the Same Now (Robert Macfarlane), Video Description = I interviewed Robert Macfarlane, a writer who has mastered the art of nature writing. What makes him fascinating isn't just that he writes about landscapes, but how he writes about them., Writer's Name = Robert Macfarlane, Publication Date = 2 months ago, Video Length = 1:29:17, View Count = 186346, Set row 4: Writer's Major Publications = Mountains of the Mind, The Wild Places, Landmarks, Underland, The Lost Words, Writing Category/Niche = Nature Writing, Career Background = Cambridge professor, Fellow of Emmanuel College, studies English literature, Set row 4: Writing Process & Methods = Immersive fieldwork, walking as research method, linguistic archaeology, detailed observation of landscapes, collaborative projects with artists, Research Methodology = Field research, walking expeditions, linguistic history, collaboration with scientists and artists, archival work on place names, Set row 4: Key Influences & Inspirations = Gerard Manley Hopkins, Edward Thomas, landscape poets, environmental science, etymology and linguistics, Unique Techniques = Neologisms and word invention, collaborative projects, multi-disciplinary approach combining literature and science, Set row 4: Writing Philosophy = Language shapes